<section xml:id="sec-radian-measure" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Radian Measure</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>There is another unit for measuring angles, called <em>radian</em>, which turns out to be more useful than degrees, particularly in calculus.</p>
    
    
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p><term>Radians</term> are a unit of angles such that,</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\boxed{\pi \text{ radians} = 180^{\circ}} \qquad \text{or, equivalently,} \qquad \boxed{2\pi \text{ radians} = 360^{\circ}}</mrow>
        </md>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <p>In other words,</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p><m>\pi</m> radians is a half-rotation.</p></li>
      <li><p><m>2\pi</m> radians is a full rotation.</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[line cap=round]
        % radius of circle
        \def\r{2cm}
        
        % axes
        \draw[-&gt;] (-\r-4,0) -- (\r+4,0) node[right] {$x$};
        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-\r-4) -- (0,\r+4) node[above] {$y$};
        
        % initial side (positive x-axis)
        \draw[-&gt;] (0,0) -- (\r,0) node[midway,below] {};
        
        % --- the pi angle in red ---
        % curved arrow for rotation from 0 to pi
        \draw[-&gt;, very thick, red]
        (0.1*\r,0) arc [start angle=0, end angle=180, radius=0.2*\r];
        % label the arc
        \node[red] at (170:0.8*\r) {$\pi$};
        % terminal side at pi
        \draw[-&gt;, very thick, red]
        (0,0) -- (180:\r) node[midway,above] {};
        
        % --- the 2pi angle in blue ---
        % curved arrow for full rotation
        \draw[-&gt;, very thick, blue]
        (0.3*\r,0) arc [start angle=0, end angle=360, radius=0.4*\r];
        % label the full-turn arc
        \node[blue] at (350:0.8*\r) {$2\pi$};
        % terminal side (coincides with initial)
        \draw[-&gt;, very thick, blue]
        (0,0) -- (\r,0) node[midway,below right] {};
        
        % center dot
        \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <ul>
      <li><p>The symbol for radians is <q>rad</q>, however the symbol is often omitted. So, if an angle has no unit, it should be assumed to be radians (and for degrees, use <m>^\circ</m>).</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>The equivalence <m>\pi = 180^{\circ}</m> can be thought of as a conversion factor, a ratio to convert between these two angle units (analogous to how 1 inch = 2.54 cm, or how 1 hour = 60 minutes).</p>
  </introduction>
  
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-converting-between-degrees-and-radians">
    <title>Converting Between Degrees and Radians</title>
    
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p><alert>Converting between degrees and radians</alert>.</p>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
            % Create two boxes for the units (closer together)
            \node[draw, rectangle, thick, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm] (rad) at (-1.5,0) {Radians};
            \node[draw, rectangle, thick, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm] (deg) at (1.5,0) {Degrees};
            
            % Arrow from radians to degrees (thicker, larger font)
            \draw[-&gt;, very thick, bend left=20] (rad.north east) to node[above] {\Large $\times \frac{180}{\pi}$} (deg.north west);
            
            % Arrow from degrees to radians (thicker, larger font)
