  <subsection xml:id="sketching-radians">
    <title>Sketching Angles in Radians</title>
    
    <p>To graph an angle in radians, it's easiest to think in terms of fractions of <m>\pi</m>. To start, recall that:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p><m>2\pi</m> is a full rotation (<m>360^{\circ}</m>)</p></li>
      <li><p><m>\pi</m> is a half rotation (<m>180^{\circ}</m>)</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Then,</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p><m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> (or half of <m>\pi</m>) is a quarter rotation (half of a half rotation), which is <m>90^{\circ}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p><m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m> (or a quarter of <m>\pi</m>) is half of a quarter rotation, which is <m>45^{\circ}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p><m>\frac{\pi}{6}</m> is <m>\pi</m> split into 6 equal pieces, which is <m>30^{\circ}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p><m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m> is <m>\pi</m> split into 3 pieces, which is <m>60^{\circ}</m>.</p></li>
    </ul>
    
