  <subsection xml:id="motivating-radians">
    <title>Motivating Radians</title>
    
    <p>Here, we will step back and explore the intuition behind radians, and how they come about to measure angles.</p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Alternate Angular Units</title>
      <p>First, it is helpful to step back and understand the idea of how angles can be measured.</p>
      <p>Degrees are a unit of rotation such that 360 degrees make a full rotation. They are useful practical applications (historically, for navigation, architecture, and astronomy), because you can divide 360 evenly into many numbers (like 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, etc.), so many common angles have whole number values (like <m>30^{\circ}, 45^{\circ}, 60^{\circ}, 90^{\circ}</m>, etc.).</p>
      <p>However, if we were starting from scratch, with no prior knowledge of degrees, we could consider other useful units of measuring angles. For example:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>The <em>gradian</em>, where a quarter rotation is defined to be 100 gradians. Then, a full rotation would be 400 gradians.</p></li>
        <li><p>Or, 1 <em>turn</em> could be defined as a full rotation. Then, a half rotation is <m>1/2</m> turns, or a quarter rotation is <m>1/4</m> turns.</p></li>
        <li><p>For units inspired by the fact that a pizza has 8 slices, a unit could be called a <em>slice</em>, defined to be <m>1/8</m>th of a full rotation. Then, 8 slices would be a full rotation.</p></li>
        <li><p>We could define 1 unit to be a quarter rotation. Then, 4 units is a full rotation.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Ultimately, units are a convention, and what units are useful or most natural depends on the context.</p>
    </example>
    
    <p>With radians, the idea is that we will measure angles based on how long the <em>arc</em> of the angle is.</p>
    
    <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Draw circle
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.2);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,0);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(55)*1.2},{sin(55)*1.2});
        
        % Draw arc
        \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (1.2,0) arc (0:55:1.2) 
        node[midway,above right] {arc (of $\theta$)};
        % Draw angle arc for theta
        \draw (0.3,0) arc (0:55:0.3);
        \node at (25:0.5) {$\theta$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <p>The longer the arc is, the bigger the angle that is swept out. The amount you rotate is proportional to how far you travel along the circle.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Small rotation <m>\rightarrow</m> small distance traveled</p></li>
      <li><p>Big rotation <m>\rightarrow</m> big distance traveled</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <image>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Left circle - small arc
        \begin{scope}[shift={(-2.5,0)}]
        % Draw circle
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.2);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,0);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(30)*1.2},{sin(30)*1.2});
        
        % Draw arc
        \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (1.2,0) arc (0:30:1.2) 
        node[midway,above right] {small arc};
        
        % Draw angle arc for theta
        \draw (0.3,0) arc (0:30:0.3);
        \node at (15:0.65) {$\theta$};
        \end{scope}
        
        % Right circle - large arc  
        \begin{scope}[shift={(2.5,0)}]
        % Draw circle
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.2);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,0);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(120)*1.2},{sin(120)*1.2});
        
        % Draw arc
        \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (1.2,0) arc (0:120:1.2) 
        node[midway,above] {large arc};
        
        % Draw angle arc for theta
        \draw (0.3,0) arc (0:120:0.3);
        \node at (60:0.5) {$\theta$};
        \end{scope}
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <p>However, just measuring the arc doesn't fully work, because the arc length depends on the size of the circle (basically, it depends on it's radius).</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>If you have a small circle, you won't have to walk very far to make a full loop.</p></li>
      <li><p>If you have a big circle, the same angle will mean you walk a lot farther.</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <image>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Caption on the left
        \node[align=left, text width=7cm] at (-6.5,0) {These two angles have the same arc length but different angle measure, because the radiuses are different};
        
        % Left circle - small radius, larger angle
        \begin{scope}[shift={(-1.5,0)}]
        % Draw circle (smaller)
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (0.8);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0.8,0);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(57.3)*0.8},{sin(57.3)*0.8});
        
        % Draw arc
        \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (0.8,0) arc (0:57.3:0.8) 
        node[midway,right] {arc};
        
        % Draw angle arc for theta
        \draw (0.25,0) arc (0:57.3:0.25);
        \node at (28:0.5) {$\theta$};
        \end{scope}
        
        % Right circle - large radius, smaller angle
        \begin{scope}[shift={(2.5,0)}]
        % Draw circle (larger)
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.6);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.6,0);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(28.65)*1.6},{sin(28.65)*1.6});
        
        % Draw arc
        \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (1.6,0) arc (0:28.65:1.6) 
        node[midway,above right] {arc};
        
        % Draw angle arc for theta
        \draw (0.4,0) arc (0:28.65:0.4);
        \node at (14:0.8) {$\theta$};
        \end{scope}
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <p>We want a measurement which purely measures rotation, that isn't affected by how big the circle is. The key idea is: even though the arc length changes when the circle gets bigger or smaller, it changes in a very predictable way. In particular, arc length is proportional to the radius.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>If you <em>double</em> the radius, the arc length <em>doubles</em>.</p></li>
      <li><p>If you <em>triple</em> the radius, the arc length <em>triples</em>.</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <example>
      <title>Arc Length Proportionality</title>
      <p>For example, for this particular angle <m>\theta</m> below, for <m>r = 4</m> cm, the arc is 8 cm, and for <m>r = 8</m> cm, the arc is 16 cm.</p>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          % Left circle - radius 4, arc 8 (2 radians)
          \begin{scope}[shift={(-2.5,0)}]
          % Draw circle
          \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1);
          
          % Center point
          \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
          
          % Draw radius lines
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below] {$4$};
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(114.6)*1},{sin(114.6)*1});
          
          % Draw arc
          \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (1,0) arc (0:114.6:1) 
          node[midway,above right] {$8$};
          
          % Draw angle arc for theta
          \draw (0.3,0) arc (0:114.6:0.3);
          \node at (57:0.5) {$\theta$};
          \end{scope}
          
          % Right circle - radius 8, arc 16 (2 radians)
          \begin{scope}[shift={(2.5,0)}]
          % Draw circle
          \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2);
          
          % Center point
          \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
          
          % Draw radius lines
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway,below] {$8$};
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- ({cos(114.6)*2},{sin(114.6)*2});
          
          % Draw arc
          \draw[ultra thick,-&gt;] (2,0) arc (0:114.6:2);
          node[midway,above right] {$16$};
          
          % Draw angle arc for theta
          \draw (0.5,0) arc (0:114.6:0.5);
          \node at (57:0.8) {$\theta$};
          \end{scope}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>While the arc lengths are different, in both scenarios, the arc length is 2 radius lengths.</p>
    </example>
    
    <p>To measure arc length, instead of using meters or centimeters or any other unit of length, we use the radius itself as the unit. In other words, we ask:</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\text{``How many radius-lengths did you travel?"}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <p>For example:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>If the radius is 4 m, and the arc length is 12 m, that is <m>\frac{12}{4} = 3</m> radius lengths of rotation.</p></li>
      <li><p>If the radius is 3 m, and the arc length is 15 m, that is <m>\frac{15}{3} = 5</m> radius lengths of rotation.</p></li>
    </ul>
    
    <image>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}    
        % Left circle - radius 4, arc 12 (3 radians = 171.9 degrees)
        \begin{scope}[shift={(-2.5,0)}]
        % Draw circle (radius proportional to 4)
        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.6);
        
        % Center point
        \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
        
        % Draw radius lines in red
        \draw[thick,red] (0,0) -- (1.6,0) node[midway,below,red] {$4$ m};
